<p class="MsoNormal">As the fall semester approaches, we review our calendars with an eye to rationing those two precious commodities:<span>&nbsp; </span>time and effort.<span>&nbsp; </span>There never seems to be enough time and we want to allocate our effort to those activities which provide the most benefit.<span>&nbsp; </span>It&rsquo;s easy to let time slip away in indecision.<span>&nbsp; </span>The phrase &ldquo;take the bull by the horns&rdquo; means to face a problem and solve it head on.<span>&nbsp; </span>We urge you to do that as you consider the fall development opportunities.<span>&nbsp; </span>A western example of taking the bull by the horns is the rodeo event called bulldogging or steer wrestling.<span>&nbsp; </span>As those of you know who attended any of the local rodeos this summer, in bulldogging the cowboy races along side of the steer, dives over, grabs it by the horns and wrestles it to the ground.<span>&nbsp; </span>Bill Pickett, a 1905 Oklahoma cowboy is credited with starting the event of bulldogging.<span>&nbsp; </span>In the beginning Bill would jump on the back of an errant animal, reach down and twist its head around, then bite its lip until it became manageable.<span>&nbsp; </span>The biting technique was similar to one used by certain cowdogs, thus the sport of &ldquo;bulldogging&rdquo; was born.<span>&nbsp; </span>As you can imagine, not a lot of cowboys wanted to bite the animal&rsquo;s lip so that aspect rather rapidly, I assume, was dropped.</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">This article provides some of the major faculty development activities for the fall semester.<span>&nbsp; </span>Take a look at your calendar and take the faculty development opportunities by the horns.<span>&nbsp; </span>Wrestle the choices down now, but try to avoid biting anyone&rsquo;s lip when you attend.</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><strong>Learning Model in Action Workshops</strong></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><br /> You can get &ldquo;hands on&rdquo; experience developing your course or syllabus with other faculty in these workshops. <span>&nbsp;</span>Based on best practices from around campus and gleaned from professional literature, each session will provide opportunities to apply Learning Model principles with a group of 10-12 colleagues. The groups will meet once a week (over three consecutive weeks).<span>&nbsp; </span>During the summer break a one day workshop will be held (see below). <span>&nbsp;</span>To register for the workshop, email <a href="mailto:Barkerde@byui.edu?subject=LMIA%20Registration">Devan Barker</a>.</p>
