<p class="MsoNormal"><a href="../../LearningAndTeaching/post/2009/07/BYU-Idaho-Faculty-Conference-on-Learning-and-Teaching.aspx"><strong>Faculty Conference on Learning &amp; Teaching</strong></a></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><strong><br /> </strong><span style="color: black;">The Faculty Development Committee is pleased to announce the BYU-Idaho Faculty Conference on Learning and Teaching.&nbsp; The conference will be held Tuesday, September 1, 2009 in the Hinckley Building.&nbsp; Under the direction of the FDC, the conference has been organized of (by and for) faculty members from across campus. <span>&nbsp;</span>Professors from the sciences to the humanities, from the Romney to the Ricks will present on a wide range of topics in a number of interesting and accessible formats. </span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color: black;"><br /> <br /> This kind of in-house conference offers rich and unique opportunities to learn from colleagues and friends.&nbsp; With the exception of time set aside for the keynote address and the lunch break, there will be six sessions running concurrently throughout the entire day.&nbsp; The topics of those concurrent sessions are diverse, ranging from the instructional use of technology to educational applications of the principle of faith.&nbsp; To register and to reserve a lunch, please email </span><a href="mailto:clementsp@byui.edu?subject=Faculty%20Conference%20Registration"><span>Peggy Clements</span></a><span style="color: black;"> by August 27th.</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><a href="../../LearningAndTeaching/post/2009/06/The-Spori-Summit-Tradition-Continues.aspx"><strong>Spori Summit</strong></a></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><strong><br /> </strong>This off-site retreat is an opportunity for members of the faculty to come together and share with each other their successes and challenges in teaching and learn about new ways to connect and support each other. <span>&nbsp;</span>In just two days, lasting friendships are formed and new ideas for teaching excellence are shared and incorporated by participants of the summit. <span>&nbsp;</span>Kevin Galbraith will facilitate beneficial presentations and activities with colleagues from our institution. <span>&nbsp;</span>The summit will be held at the Quickwater Ranch in Victor, ID on October 8-9<sup>th</sup> (Thursday afternoon and Friday).<span>&nbsp; </span>To register, email <a href="mailto:schmidtb@byui.edu?subject=Spori%20Summit%20Registration">Brian Schmidt</a>.</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><strong>Course Tune-up Consultations </strong></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><br /> Would you like the opportunity to explore ideas for your course with a colleague? <span>&nbsp;</span>Are you considering adjustments to your course design? <span>&nbsp;</span>Are you wondering how to better align your course with the Learning Model? <span>&nbsp;</span>&ldquo;Course Tune-up Consultations&rdquo; is a new service that allows you to work individually with a two-person consultation team on the design of your course(s). <span>&nbsp;</span>Each consultation team includes a member of the faculty and a member of the Instructional Development group. <span>&nbsp;</span>Consultations will last 1-2 hours. <span>&nbsp;</span><a href="http://www.byui.edu/learningandteaching/course_tune_up/">Click here</a> to schedule an appointment.</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><strong><span style="color: black;">Brown Bag Lunches</span></strong><span style="color: black;"> </span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color: black;"><br /> We invite you to plan to attend the Faculty Development Committee&rsquo;s Brown Bag Lunches to discuss learning and teaching and to share ideas. <span>&nbsp;</span>The purpose of these gatherings isn&rsquo;t to provide solutions for teaching problems but to &ldquo;stir the pot&rdquo; by presenting new perspectives and by highlighting real-world examples. <span>&nbsp;</span>We&rsquo;ll gather in September, October, and November during the fall semester. &nbsp;Watch for an email announcement regarding the September meeting once the fall semester is underway.</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><strong>Learning Communities</strong></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><br /> A BYU-Idaho Learning Community is a group of faculty members who meet on a regular basis to share ideas on ways to improve learning and teaching. &nbsp;Each group (generally comprised of 8-12 members) focuses on a particular topic for the semester. &nbsp;This fall <a href="../../directory/employees/OfficeHours.aspx?User=PIEPERR">Richard Pieper</a> will lead a learning community on assessment and <a href="../../directory/employees/OfficeHours.aspx?User=RIGGINSW">Bill Riggins</a> will lead a group considering ways to improve collaborative activities with problems, projects and questions. &nbsp;Generally learning communities meet once a week for an hour. &nbsp;Often these groups produce a resource for the Learning and Teaching website or sponsor some sort of training such as a Brown Bag to share some of their findings. &nbsp;To join one of these communities, contact one of the group leaders.</p>
